  "q_43342": {
    "question_id": 43342,
    "question_text": "Will any host nation (USA, Mexico or Canada) reach the semifinals of the 2026 World Cup?",
    "probability": 0.71,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Any Host Nation Reach 2026 World Cup Semifinals?\n\n## (a) Time Left Until Resolution\nThe tournament runs June 11 - July 19, 2026. Today is June 13, 2026. We are **6 days into the tournament** with group stage matches currently underway. Resolution occurs in approximately **36 days**.\n\n## (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changes\nGroup stage matches are being played now. Based on current FIFA rankings (USA #16, Mexico #15, Canada #30), we would expect:\n- **USA and Mexico**: Likely to progress from group stage as they're ranked in the top 20\n- **Canada**: Ranked #30, historically weaker - lower probability of advancing\n- **From group stage to semifinals**: Requires winning/advancing through Round of 16 and quarterfinals\n\nThe status quo suggests at least one of the three (USA or Mexico) has a reasonable chance to reach semifinals, elevated by home advantage.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO Outcome\n- All three host nations are eliminated by the quarterfinal stage or earlier\n- USA or Mexico struggle in group stage, fail to advance (unlikely given rankings)\n- One or both of USA/Mexico advance from groups but lose in Round of 16 or quarterfinals\n- Home advantage is insufficient to overcome stronger opponents from Europe/South America\n- All three nations happen to face elite teams (France, Argentina, Germany, Brazil) in knockout rounds\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES Outcome\n- At least one of USA or Mexico advances through quarters\n- Home advantage provides meaningful boost (3-5% estimated by research)\n- Favorable bracket positioning helps one nation avoid elite teams until semis\n- Mexican or US team performs cohesively through knockout stages\n- Home crowd advantage proves decisive in tight matches during Round of 16 or quarterfinals\n\n## (e) Base Rate \u2014 How Often Do Similar Events Occur?\n\n**Historical data on host nations reaching semifinals:**\n- In the modern World Cup era (1970-2022), examining host nation performance:\n  - 1974 West Germany (hosted): Reached final \u2713\n  - 1978 Argentina (hosted): Reached final \u2713\n  - 1982 Spain (hosted): Reached semifinals \u2713\n  - 1986 Mexico (hosted): Reached quarterfinals \u2717\n  - 1994 USA (hosted): Reached Round of 16 \u2717\n  - 1998 France (hosted): Reached final \u2713\n  - 2002 South Korea (hosted): Reached semifinals \u2713\n  - 2006 Germany (hosted): Reached final \u2713\n  - 2010 South Africa (hosted): Reached quarterfinals \u2717\n  - 2014 Brazil (hosted): Reached semifinals \u2713\n  - 2018 Russia (hosted): Reached quarterfinals \u2717\n  - 2022 Qatar (hosted): Reached group stage \u2717\n\n**At least one host nation reaching semifinals: 7 out of 12 instances = ~58%**\n\nHowever, this includes multiple hosts. When there are **3 co-hosts**, the probability increases substantially because we only need **one** to reach semis.\n\nFor individual host nations (single host):\n- Reaching semifinals: ~58%\n- With three hosts, probability that **at least one** reaches semis increases due to:\n  - Three independent(ish) chances\n  - Cumulative probability advantage\n  - Estimated combined: **70-75%**\n\n## (f) How Current Data/News Moves Me From Base Rate\n\n**Positive factors toward YES:**\n1. **Rankings support**: USA (#16) and Mexico (#15) are solid top-20 teams, stronger than historical average hosts\n2. **Home advantage documented**: Research shows ~3-5% performance boost; in tight tournaments this can be decisive\n3. **Multiple hosts = multiple chances**: Three nations means only one needs to advance\n4. **Geography/travel**: No long intercontinental travel burden like typical hosts\n5. **Established football infrastructure**: All three have professional leagues and coaching systems\n\n**Negative factors toward NO:**\n1. **Early tournament stage**: We're only 6 days in; many surprises can occur\n2. **Canada's weakness**: #30 ranking makes Canadian path to semis extremely unlikely (~5%)\n3. **Historical: 2 prior US/Mexico hosts underperformed**: USA 1994 (R16), Mexico 1986 (QF) - neither reached semis\n4. **Competitive field**: 2026 will feature strong traditional powers (France, Argentina, Germany, Brazil, England, Spain)\n5. **Three hosts may dilute advantage**: Having to share the host benefit across three nations; infrastructure challenges with co-hosting\n\n**Net adjustment**: The strong rankings of USA/Mexico and documented home advantage support moving slightly above base rate, but the historical underperformance of these specific nations when hosting, plus the difficulty of reaching semifinals (top 4 of 32 teams) suggests staying near or slightly above the base rate.\n\n## (g) Community Prediction Divergence\n\nI don't have access to specific community forecaster predictions for this question. However, I would note:\n- **Casual observers** might overweight home advantage and recent team quality\n- **Serious forecasters** should recognize that semifinals = top 4, a high bar requiring ~2 consecutive knockout wins\n- The base rate of ~58% for individual hosts is well-established; with three hosts, ~70-75% seems appropriate\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nStarting from base rate of ~70% (at least one of three host nations reaches semis in typical tournament conditions):\n- USA/Mexico rankings are solid and support advancement\n- Home advantage is real but modest in impact\n- Historical precedent shows host nations do better than random\n- But reaching **semifinals specifically** (not just quarterfinals) is difficult\n- Canada is very unlikely; everything rests on USA/Mexico\n- Both USA and Mexico have historical precedent of underperforming as hosts relative to expectations\n\nThe combination of:\n- 3 host nations (multiplicative probability boost)\n- Solid rankings for 2 of them\n- Documented home advantage\n- But historical underperformance of USA/Mexico hosts specifically\n- And the difficulty of reaching semifinals\n\nLeads me to estimate: **71%**\n\n**Probability: 71%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43343": {
    "question_id": 43343,
    "question_text": "Will any match of the 2026 FIFA World Cup be delayed by more than 30 minutes due to extreme heat?",
    "probability": 0.12,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will any 2026 FIFA World Cup match be delayed >30 minutes due to extreme heat?\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe 2026 FIFA World Cup runs from June 12 to July 12, 2026. Today is June 13, 2026, which means we are approximately 1 day into the tournament with 29 days remaining. The vast majority of matches have yet to be played.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf current conditions persist, matches will proceed with mandatory cooling breaks as instituted by FIFA. No official delays beyond the standard break structure have occurred in the first day of matches. The status quo is that FIFA's cooling break protocol is sufficient to manage heat, and matches proceed on schedule.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- FIFA's mandatory cooling breaks prove effective in managing heat stress for players and officials\n- While WBGT temperatures exceed 28\u00b0C in multiple venues (as expected in 14 of 16 cities), the breaks + water provision + shade access sufficiently mitigate health/performance concerns\n- No match is delayed by 30+ consecutive minutes with explicit heat attribution\n- Tournament completes as scheduled without heat-related match postponements\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- During later stages of the tournament, extreme heat conditions (WBGT well above 28\u00b0C) combined with high humidity create conditions where mandatory breaks alone prove insufficient\n- FIFA/referees determine that player safety requires a substantial delay (30+ minutes) with explicit recognition that heat is the cause\n- A match experiences a suspension that meets the specific resolution criteria: \u226530 consecutive minutes delayed with official heat attribution\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Historical context for heat-related match delays in major football tournaments:**\n- 2022 Qatar World Cup: Matches had scheduled earlier kickoff times (7pm local time) to manage heat, but NO matches were officially delayed/postponed due to heat despite extreme conditions (40\u00b0C+)\n- 2019 Copa America: No official heat-related match delays\n- Previous World Cups: Heat management through scheduling rather than match delays\n- Professional football generally avoids outright postponements due to heat\u2014instead using scheduling, breaks, and hydration protocols\n\nThe historical base rate for official match delays >30 minutes explicitly attributed to heat in major football tournaments is approximately **2-5%** (rare but not unprecedented).\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES:**\n- Scientific evidence confirms 14 of 16 host cities will experience extreme heat\n- FIFPRO explicitly recommends delays when WBGT exceeds 28\u00b0C\n- The 2026 tournament is specifically in North America (Mexico, USA, Canada) in June-July, historically very hot in these regions\n- We're now 1 day in with 29 days of tournament play remaining\u2014many matches in hottest periods ahead\n- FIFA's mandatory cooling breaks may be viewed as insufficient by FIFA officials themselves if conditions are exceptionally severe\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO:**\n- FIFA has pre-emptively implemented mandatory cooling breaks for ALL matches (not just hot ones), suggesting they have confidence in managing heat without delays\n- This cooling break protocol is more comprehensive than past tournaments\n- Professional football has strong institutional resistance to match delays (scheduling, revenue, logistics)\n- Even in Qatar (40\u00b0C+), despite extreme conditions, no official heat-related match delays occurred\n- \"Explicit attribution to heat\" is a high bar\u2014FIFA may cite \"player welfare\" or \"medical assessment\" without specifically naming heat\n\n## (g) Community prediction\n\nI don't have access to current community probability estimates for this specific question. However, if the community is around 15-25%, I would diverge moderately upward because:\n- The combination of pre-tournament warnings about extreme heat in 14/16 cities + scientific evidence + explicit FIFPRO recommendations suggests this is genuinely a higher-risk scenario than typical tournaments\n- The 29 days remaining provide substantial opportunity for one match to meet the criteria\n- However, I would still diverge downward from >40% because FIFA's proactive cooling breaks + historical institutional resistance to delays suggests they've modeled this and believe it manageable\n\n---\n\n## Probability Reasoning\n\n**Anchor on base rate:** ~3% (historical rate for official heat-related match delays in major tournaments)\n\n**Adjustment factors:**\n- Extreme heat in 14/16 venues: +8-10 percentage points (substantively different from past tournaments)\n- Mandatory cooling breaks already in place suggests FIFA confidence: -5 percentage points (they've de-risked)\n- Qatar precedent (40\u00b0C, no delays): -3 percentage points (institutional resistance is strong)\n- \"Explicit attribution\" requirement: -2 percentage points (high evidentiary bar)\n- 29 days remaining / 64 total matches = ample opportunity for one event: +4 percentage points\n\n**Adjusted estimate: 3% + 10% - 5% - 3% - 2% + 4% = 7%**\n\nThis reflects:\n- Substantially elevated risk vs. historical norm due to documented extreme heat forecasts\n- Strong institutional and mechanical protections (cooling breaks) that have worked in past extreme scenarios\n- High bar for explicit heat attribution\n- Meaningful but still-low probability given football's strong preference to play matches as scheduled\n\n**Probability: 12%**\n\n(I adjust upward from 7% to 12% given that this is one of the first World Cups with pre-tournament extreme heat warnings across multiple cities simultaneously, and the cooling break protocol may prove inadequate if conditions are even more extreme than managed in Qatar\u2014a tail risk worth capturing.)",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_43888": {
    "question_id": 43888,
    "question_text": "Will the average monthly price per kWh of electricity in the U.S. break $0.40 before the end of 2030 (doubling recent values)?",
    "probability": 0.13,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will US Average Monthly Electricity Price Break $0.40/kWh Before End of 2030?\n\n## (a) Time Left Until Resolution\nFrom June 2026 to December 2030: **4.5 years** or approximately 54 months of data collection remaining.\n\n## (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changes\nIf trends continue as they have in recent years:\n- April 2026 price: $0.194/kWh\n- Historical growth rate: approximately 2-3% annually in recent years\n- If 2.5% annual growth continues: $0.194 \u00d7 (1.025)^4.5 \u2248 $0.220/kWh by end of 2030\n- **Status quo suggests NO resolution** - price would reach only ~$0.22, well short of $0.40\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO Outcome\n- Energy supply expansion keeps pace with demand growth\n- Natural gas and renewable energy maintain competitive pricing\n- No major geopolitical disruption affecting energy markets\n- Demand growth remains moderate due to efficiency improvements\n- No sustained supply shocks lasting multiple years\n- Historical growth rates of 2-3% annually persist\n- Major structural changes in energy markets don't occur\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES Outcome\nWould require a near-doubling of electricity prices in ~4.5 years, implying ~15-17% annual growth. Paths to YES include:\n- **Supply constraints**: Insufficient generation capacity expansion, renewable permitting delays, grid investment bottlenecks\n- **Demand surge**: Massive data center growth, industrial electrification, EV charging acceleration outpaces supply\n- **Energy crisis**: Major sustained disruption (war affecting energy markets, cyber attack on grid, climate disaster reducing capacity)\n- **Policy shocks**: Carbon taxes, restrictions on fossil fuels without equivalent renewable capacity\n- **Geopolitical**: Major conflict disrupting global energy supplies\n- **Financial**: Dollar devaluation making imported energy more expensive\n\n## (e) Base Rate - Similar Events\nLooking at historical precedent:\n- US electricity prices from 2000-2024 have shown ~2-3% annual growth with occasional spikes\n- The 2021-2022 energy crisis saw some regional spikes but didn't sustain\n- California's crisis (2000-2001) saw temporary ~3x increases but wasn't national average\n- **Doubling over 4.5 years (15-17% CAGR)** is historically rare in US electricity markets outside crisis periods\n- Even during the 2021-22 energy crisis, national average didn't exceed $0.30/kWh\n- Base rate for such dramatic sustained increases: **~5-10%** historically\n\n## (f) Current Data/News Moving From Base Rate\n\n**Upward pressure factors:**\n- Strong demand growth from AI/data centers (ongoing acceleration)\n- Grid modernization costs rising\n- Renewable integration complexity increasing grid costs\n- Permitting challenges for new generation capacity\n- Global commodity price volatility\n- Labor/material cost inflation in energy sector\n\n**Downward pressure factors (stronger):**\n- Massive renewable capacity additions coming online (solar/wind historically cost-competitive at grid scale)\n- Battery storage costs declining 10-15% annually, improving grid economics\n- Energy efficiency improvements continuing\n- Nuclear renaissance uncertain but some new builds progressing\n- Natural gas remains abundant domestically\n- Recent trend shows moderate growth, not acceleration\n\n**Recent context**: April 2026 at $0.194 shows prices have grown only modestly from historical levels despite inflation. This suggests structural equilibrium around 2-3% growth, not accelerating toward 15%+ needed for YES.\n\nThe data suggests we're in a **normal growth regime**, not a shortage regime. For YES, we'd need a fundamental shift to a shortage regime - possible but not the base case.\n\n**Adjustment**: +2% for genuine supply/demand risks from AI boom, but this remains within normal growth bounds. Move from 5-10% base to approximately **12-15%**.\n\n## (g) Community Prediction Divergence\nNo specific community forecast provided in the question. My estimate of ~13% would likely be **lower than Metaculus base rates** for this question, as forecasting communities often:\n- Overweight near-term trends\n- Overestimate supply disruption probability\n- Underestimate technological solutions to capacity\n- Show recency bias from 2021-22 energy crisis\n\nHowever, the mathematical requirement (15-17% annual growth from current $0.194) is genuinely extreme and historically rare, which anchors skepticism.\n\n## Probability: 13%",
    "status": "success"
  },
