ing 2026 result (Community loss) would normally suggest slightly lower probability for a Community victory, but that's one data point.\n\n**(g) Community prediction comparison:**\nI have no information about an existing community prediction on this meta-question or its magnitude, so I cannot evaluate divergence.\n\n## Critical Limitation\n\n**I cannot access live Metaculus leaderboard data** showing current tournament standings, scores, remaining questions, or performance trajectories. This information would be essential for an accurate probability estimate. A well-calibrated forecast requires knowing:\n- Current score differentials\n- How much of the tournament remains\n- Historical volatility in the scoring\n\n## Probability Assessment\n\nGiven:\n- One prior tournament result (Community loss)\n- No access to current leaderboard positioning\n- Uncertainty about remaining questions and difficulty\n- Dylan Matthews has strong domain expertise (economics, policy, global health)\n- But community aggregation is theoretically powerful\n\nI'm anchoring near 50% (reflecting genuine uncertainty) with a modest downward adjustment based on Spring 2026 result.\n\n**Probability: 45%**\n\nThis reflects that while community predictions have theoretical advantages, the Spring 2026 loss is directional evidence, and without current leaderboard data, I'm legitimately uncertain. A forecaster with access to current tournament standings could likely produce a much better estimate.",
